[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static application security testing (SAST) differs from dynamic application security testing (DAST) in that SAST is a form of static analysis performed when the program is not actually executing, whereas DAST is a form of dynamic analysis done when the program is running.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Static analysis is performed when the program is not actually executing; dynamic analysis is done when the program is running.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "SAST tools analyze the source code for issues such as syntax errors, structural flaws, improper data usage, and incorrect sequences without executing the program, while DAST tools monitor the program's behavior during execution to capture the state of events and report on the program's behavior.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Static Analysis. Several tools can analyze a source program before it is run. Tools that investigate the correctness of a program or set of components can be grouped into four types: Code analyzer, Structure checker, Data analyzer, Sequence checker.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Dynamic Analysis. Many times, systems are difficult to test because several parallel operations are being performed concurrently. ... Automated tools enable the test team to capture the state of events during the execution of a program by preserving a 'snapshot' of conditions. These tools are sometimes called program monitors because they watch and report the program's behavior.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding the phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) at which each should be applied, static analysis (SAST) is typically applied early in the development process before the program is run, allowing detection of faults early, while dynamic analysis (DAST) is applied during or after the program execution phase to monitor runtime behavior and capture issues that occur during execution.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Static analysis is performed when the program is not actually executing; dynamic analysis is done when the program is running.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, a code analyzer can generate a symbol table to record where a variable is first defined and when it is used, supporting test strategies such as definition-use testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Dynamic Analysis. Many times, systems are difficult to test because several parallel operations are being performed concurrently. ... Automated tools enable the test team to capture the state of events during the execution of a program by preserving a 'snapshot' of conditions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

