[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The concept of decomposition in software design involves breaking down a system into smaller, manageable software units such as components, subsystems, modules, classes, and packages.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "No matter which design approach we use, the resulting design is likely to refer to several types of software units, such as component, subsystem, runtime process, module, class, package, library, or procedure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Decomposition methods, including functional, feature-oriented, data-oriented, process-oriented, event-oriented, and object-oriented design, help organize these software units by focusing on different aspects such as functions, features, data, processes, events, or objects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Functional decomposition: This method partitions functions or requirements into modules... - Feature-oriented design: This method is a type of functional decomposition that assigns features to modules... - Data-oriented decomposition: This method focuses on how data will be partitioned into modules... - Process-oriented decomposition: This method partitions the system into concurrent processes... - Event-oriented decomposition: This method focuses on the events that the system must handle and assigns responsibility for events to different modules... - Object-oriented design: This method assigns objects to modules.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A layered architecture typically organizes software units into layers, each representing a level of abstraction or responsibility, which can be seen as a form of decomposition where each layer contains related modules or components.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Domain-Driven Design (DDD), a \"Bounded Context\" defines a boundary within which a particular domain model applies consistently, effectively partitioning the system into distinct conceptual areas.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Relating this to decomposition in layered architecture, a Bounded Context can be viewed as a higher-level software unit or subsystem that encapsulates a specific domain model and its associated components, modules, and processes, maintaining clear boundaries and interfaces with other contexts.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the DDD concept of a Bounded Context aligns with the principle of decomposition by defining clear boundaries for software units that correspond to distinct domain areas, which can be implemented as subsystems or components within a layered architecture.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook recommends using neural networks and tree-based techniques as machine learning methods for automating effort estimation beyond the COCOMO II model.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Srinivasan and Fisher (1995) used Kemerer's data (Kemerer 1989) with a statistical technique called a regression tree; they produced predictions more accurate than those of the original COCOMO model and SLIM, a proprietary commercial model. However, their results were not as good as those produced by a neural network or a model based on function points. Briand, Basili, and Thomas (1992) obtained better results from using a tree induction technique, using the Kemerer and COCOMO datasets. Porter and Selby (1990) also used a tree-based approach; they constructed a decision tree that identifies which project, process, and product characteristics may be useful in predicting likely effort.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 3.13 Shepperd's feed-forward neural network.]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1042_1043_257"
            }
