    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Microservices architecture differs from service-oriented architecture (SOA) primarily in the granularity and independence of services.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In SOA, services are typically larger and share a common communication protocol and enterprise service bus (ESB), whereas microservices are smaller, independently deployable units that communicate over lightweight protocols.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When migrating from a monolith to microservices, the tradeoffs include increased complexity in managing distributed systems, the need for robust DevOps practices, and potential challenges in data consistency and inter-service communication.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, microservices offer benefits such as improved scalability, flexibility in technology choices, and faster deployment cycles.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

