    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Test-Driven Development (TDD), the exact sequence of the Red-Green-Refactor cycle is as follows: first, you write a failing test (Red), then write just enough code to make the test pass (Green), and finally refactor the code to improve its structure without changing its behavior (Refactor).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Red-Green-Refactor cycle is a fundamental practice in TDD where you first write a failing test (Red), then write code to pass the test (Green), and finally refactor the code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is recommended to perform multiple test iterations of this cycle before committing code, typically around three to five iterations, to ensure the code is well-tested and clean.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Developers are encouraged to repeat the Red-Green-Refactor cycle multiple times, usually three to five iterations, before committing the code to maintain quality and stability.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO/IEC 25010 quality characteristics replace the older McCall quality factors by providing a hierarchical model with six major attributes contributing to software quality.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the early 1990s, the software engineering community attempted to consolidate the many views of quality into one model that could act as a worldwide standard for measuring software quality. The result was ISO 9126, a hierarchical model with six major attributes contributing to quality (International Standardization Organization 1991).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO 9126 model includes the following quality characteristics: Functionality, Reliability, Usability, Efficiency, Maintainability, and Portability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 12.3 illustrates the hierarchy, and Table 12.4 defines the major attributes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_5161_5161_1179"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "TABLE 12.4 ISO 9126 Quality Characteristics ... Functionality ... Reliability ... Usability ... Efficiency ... Maintainability ... Portability",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "McCall's quality factors include Correctness, Reliability, Efficiency, Integrity, Usability, Maintainability, Testability, Flexibility, Portability, Reusability, and Interoperability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_188_188_57"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO 9126 model maps to McCall's factors by grouping similar attributes under broader categories such as Functionality (covering Correctness and Integrity), Reliability, Efficiency, Usability, Maintainability, and Portability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One major difference between the ISO model and those of McCall and Boehm is that the ISO hierarchy is strict: each right-hand characteristic is related only to exactly one left-hand attribute.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These models, and many others, are helpful in articulating just what it is that we value in the software we build and use.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

